"# Chapter 12: Secondary Motion

A flag whips in the wind. The fabric reaches its peak just after the pole stops moving. A dancer spins, and her scarf trails behind, catching up a heartbeat late. A dog skids to a halt, but its ears swing forward, then back, then settle. This trailing, lagging, follow-through motion is what makes a body read as real—as something with parts that have their own weight, their own drag, their own time.

Primary motion is the main action: the jump, the turn, the stop. Secondary motion is everything that *follows*—the parts that react to the main move, each with its own timing. Overlapping action means different parts move on different schedules. Drag and lag mean trailing parts arrive late. Follow-through means motion continues past the primary stop, then settles.

This chapter drills:
- **Drag**: trailing parts that lag behind the leader
- **Follow-through**: motion that continues past the primary stop
- **Overlapping action**: different parts on different timings
- **Settle**: the gradual return to rest after the main move ends

We'll compose ideas from earlier chapters—easing, timing, oscillation, forces—to build motion that reads as a *body with parts*, not a single rigid unit.

---

## The simplest secondary: a leader and a follower

One entity moves. A second entity chases it, always trying to catch up. The chaser's lag *is* the secondary motion.

```scheme
(let* ((leader (world/spawn 100 150))
       (follower (world/spawn 100 150)))
  (entity/sprite! leader \"circle\" 12 \"blue\")
  (entity/sprite! follower \"circle\" 8 \"cyan\")
  
  ;; leader moves in a slow arc
  (motion/arc leader 300 150 60 120)
  
  ;; follower tries to catch up every frame
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (let* ((lx (entity/x leader))
             (ly (entity/y leader))
             (fx (entity/x follower))
             (fy (entity/y follower))
             (dx (- lx fx))
             (dy (- ly fy)))
        ;; move 10% of the way toward leader each frame
        (entity/move! follower (* dx 0.1) (* dy 0.1))
        (when (world/alive? leader)
          (world/after 1 (world/current-callback)))))))
```

[VISUAL: Blue circle arcs smoothly to the right. Cyan circle trails behind in a smooth curve, always lagging.]

The follower never quite catches up—it's always 10% of the distance behind. That constant lag creates the secondary trail.

---

## A chain of followers

Three entities, each chasing the one in front. The third lags the most.

```scheme
(let* ((a (world/spawn 100 150))
       (b (world/spawn 100 150))
       (c (world/spawn 100 150)))
  (entity/sprite! a \"circle\" 12 \"red\")
  (entity/sprite! b \"circle\" 10 \"orange\")
  (entity/sprite! c \"circle\" 8 \"yellow\")
  
  ;; leader moves in a wide arc
  (motion/arc a 350 200 80 180)
  
  ;; b chases a, c chases b
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (let ((chase (lambda (follower leader rate)
                     (let* ((lx (entity/x leader))
                            (ly (entity/y leader))
                            (fx (entity/x follower))
                            (fy (entity/y follower))
                            (dx (- lx fx))
                            (dy (- ly fy)))
                       (entity/move! follower (* dx rate) (* dy rate))))))
        (chase b a 0.12)
        (chase c b 0.12)
        (when (world/alive? a)
          (world/after 1 (world/current-callback)))))))
```

[VISUAL: Red circle arcs smoothly. Orange follows with slight lag. Yellow trails furthest behind, tracing a gentler curve.]

Each link in the chain amplifies the lag. The tail of the chain moves last, and its path is the smoothest.

---

## A tail that drags

A creature moves forward. Its tail is a chain of segments, each following the one in front. The tail whips and settles as the creature changes direction.

```scheme
(let* ((head (world/spawn 100 150))
       (tail-1 (world/spawn 100 150))
       (tail-2 (world/spawn 100 150))
       (tail-3 (world/spawn 100 150))
       (t 0))
  (entity/sprite! head \"circle\" 14 \"darkgreen\")
  (entity/sprite! tail-1 \"circle\" 11 \"green\")
  (entity/sprite! tail-2 \"circle\" 9 \"limegreen\")
  (entity/sprite! tail-3 \"circle\" 7 \"palegreen\")
  
  ;; head moves in a figure-eight pattern
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (set! t (+ t 0.05))
      (let ((x (+ 200 (* 80 (dsin t))))
            (y (+ 150 (* 60 (dsin (* t 2))))))
        (entity/set-pos! head x y))
      
      ;; tail segments chase with varying lag rates
      (let ((chase (lambda (follower leader rate)
                     (let* ((lx (entity/x leader))
                            (ly (entity/y leader))
                            (fx (entity/x follower))
                            (fy (entity/y follower))
                            (dx (- lx fx))
                            (dy (- ly fy)))
                       (entity/move! follower (* dx rate) (* dy rate))))))
        (chase tail-1 head 0.15)
        (chase tail-2 tail-1 0.15)
        (chase tail-3 tail-2 0.15))
      
      (world/after 1 (world/current-callback)))))
```

[VISUAL: Dark green head traces a figure-eight. Three lighter green circles follow, each lagging more, creating a sinuous trailing tail that whips through the curves.]

The tail is always playing catch-up. When the head changes direction, the tail swings wide, then gradually settles into the new path.

---

## Follow-through: motion continues past the stop

A ball rolls to a stop. Its antenna continues to sway back and forth, gradually settling.

```scheme
(let* ((ball (world/spawn 50 200))
       (antenna (world/spawn 50 180))
       (stopped #f)
       (sway-vel 0))
  (entity/sprite! ball \"circle\" 16 \"purple\")
  (entity/sprite! antenna \"circle\" 6 \"violet\")
  
  ;; ball glides to a stop
  (motion/glide-to ball 300 200 90)
  
  ;; after 90 frames, ball has stopped, but antenna keeps swaying
  (world/after 90
    (lambda ()
      (set! stopped #t)
      (set! sway-vel 4.0)))  ;; initial sway velocity
  
  ;; antenna follows ball, then sways when stopped
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (if stopped
          (let* ((ball-x (entity/x ball))
                 (ball-y (entity/y ball))
                 (ant-x (entity/x antenna))
                 (offset (- ant-x ball-x)))
            ;; sway back and forth with damping
            (set! sway-vel (+ sway-vel (* offset -0.1)))
            (set! sway-vel (* sway-vel 0.95))  ;; damping
            (entity/set-pos! antenna (+ ball-x sway-vel) (- ball-y 20)))
          (let ((ball-x (entity/x ball))
                (ball-y (entity/y ball)))
            (entity/set-pos! antenna ball-x (- ball-y 20))))
      
      (world/after 1 (world/current-callback)))))
```

[VISUAL: Purple ball glides smoothly from left to right, then stops. Small violet circle rides atop it, swaying left and right with decreasing amplitude, gradually settling to rest above the ball.]

The primary motion ends at frame 90, but the antenna's secondary motion continues—it oscillates with damping until it settles.

---

## A pendulum that settles

An entity swings like a pendulum after an impulse. The swing gradually dampens to stillness.

```scheme
(let* ((anchor-x 200)
       (anchor-y 50)
       (bob (world/spawn anchor-x (+ anchor-y 100)))
       (angle 1.2)  ;; initial displacement (radians)
       (angular-vel 0))
  (entity/sprite! bob \"circle\" 12 \"brown\")
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      ;; pendulum physics: angular acceleration proportional to sin(angle)
      (let ((angular-accel (* (dsin angle) -0.02)))
        (set! angular-vel (+ angular-vel angular-accel))
        (set! angular-vel (* angular-vel 0.995))  ;; damping
        (set! angle (+ angle angular-vel))
        
        ;; position bob at the end of the pendulum arm
        (let* ((arm-length 100)
               (x (+ anchor-x (* arm-length (dsin angle))))
               (y (+ anchor-y (* arm-length (dcos angle)))))
          (entity/set-pos! bob x y)))
      
      (world/after 1 (world/current-callback)))))
```

[VISUAL: Brown circle swings back and forth in a pendulum arc, each swing smaller than the last, gradually coming to rest at the bottom of the arc.]

The pendulum's swing is follow-through—it continues long after the initial displacement, settling toward equilibrium.

---

## Overlapping action: different parts, different timings

A character stops. Its body stops first, then its head, then its antenna. Each part arrives on its own schedule.

```scheme
(let* ((body (world/spawn 100 150))
       (head (world/spawn 100 130))
       (antenna (world/spawn 100 110))
       (t 0))
  (entity/sprite! body \"circle\" 18 \"teal\")
  (entity/sprite! head \"circle\" 12 \"cyan\")
  (entity/sprite! antenna \"circle\" 6 \"lightcyan\")
  
  ;; body moves, then stops at t=60
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (set! t (+ t 1))
      (cond
        ;; body moves for 60 frames, then stops
        ((<= t 60)
         (entity/move! body 3 0))
        
        ;; body stopped, head catches up over 30 frames
        ((<= t 90)
         (let* ((bx (entity/x body))
                (hx (entity/x head))
                (dx (- bx hx)))
           (entity/move! head (* dx 0.15) 0)))
        
        ;; head stopped, antenna catches up over 40 frames
        ((<= t 130)
         (let* ((hx (entity/x head))
                (ax (entity/x antenna))
                (dx (- hx ax)))
           (entity/move! antenna (* dx 0.1) 0))))
      
      ;; all parts track vertical position relative to body
      (let ((by (entity/y body)))
        (entity/set-pos! head (entity/x head) (- by 20))
        (entity/set-pos! antenna (entity/x antenna) (- by 40)))
      
      (when (<= t 130)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Teal circle slides right and stops. Cyan circle trails behind, then glides to rest atop it. Light cyan circle lags furthest, finally settling atop the stack.]

The body, head, and antenna each move on different timings. The arrivals overlap, creating a cascading settle.

---

## A scarf that trails

A character runs forward, then stops. A scarf trails behind, then swings forward past the character, then settles back.

```scheme
(let* ((character (world/spawn 100 150))
       (scarf (world/spawn 80 150))
       (char-vx 0)
       (scarf-vx 0)
       (t 0))
  (entity/sprite! character \"circle\" 16 \"maroon\")
  (entity/sprite! scarf \"circle\" 10 \"pink\")
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (set! t (+ t 1))
      
      ;; character accelerates, then decelerates to a stop
      (cond
        ((<= t 30)
         (set! char-vx 5))
        ((<= t 50)
         (set! char-vx (* char-vx 0.85)))  ;; brake
        (else
         (set! char-vx 0)))
      
      (entity/move! character char-vx 0)
      
      ;; scarf tries to follow character, with drag
      (let* ((cx (entity/x character))
             (sx (entity/x scarf))
             (dx (- cx sx))
             (pull (* dx 0.08)))
        (set! scarf-vx (+ scarf-vx pull))
        (set! scarf-vx (* scarf-vx 0.92))  ;; air resistance
        (entity/move! scarf scarf-vx 0))
      
      (when (<= t 200)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Maroon circle accelerates right, then brakes to a stop. Pink circle trails behind during acceleration, then swings past the character as it stops, then oscillates back and forth with decreasing amplitude, finally settling just behind.]

The scarf's momentum carries it forward even as the character stops. It overshoots, then settles—classic follow-through.

---

## A ponytail that bounces

A character jumps. Its ponytail lags during the ascent, then stretches downward at the peak, then compresses on landing.

```scheme
(let* ((head (world/spawn 200 200))
       (ponytail (world/spawn 200 215))
       (vy 0)
       (gravity 0.3)
       (on-ground #t)
       (pt-vy 0))
  (entity/sprite! head \"circle\" 14 \"chocolate\")
  (entity/sprite! ponytail \"circle\" 8 \"tan\")
  
  ;; jump at frame 30
  (world/after 30
    (lambda ()
      (set! vy -8)
      (set! on-ground #f)))
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      ;; head physics
      (unless on-ground
        (set! vy (+ vy gravity))
        (entity/move! head 0 vy)
        (when (>= (entity/y head) 200)
          (entity/set-pos! head (entity/x head) 200)
          (set! vy 0)
          (set! on-ground #t)))
      
      ;; ponytail follows head with springy lag
      (let* ((hx (entity/x head))
             (hy (entity/y head))
             (py (entity/y ponytail))
             (target-y (+ hy 15))
             (dy (- target-y py))
             (accel (* dy 0.12)))
        (set! pt-vy (+ pt-vy accel))
        (set! pt-vy (* pt-vy 0.88))  ;; damping
        (entity/set-pos! ponytail hx (+ py pt-vy)))
      
      (when (<= (world/frame) 180)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Brown circle jumps upward in an arc, lands, and settles. Tan circle below it lags during ascent, stretches downward at the peak (hanging in the air), then bounces and compresses on landing, gradually settling back to rest position below the head.]

The ponytail's secondary motion is driven by a spring—it lags, stretches, compresses, and settles, all in reaction to the primary jump motion.

---

## A flag in the wind

A flagpole tilts left and right. A flag at the top trails behind, whipping and fluttering.

```scheme
(let* ((pole (world/spawn 200 200))
       (flag (world/spawn 200 160))
       (pole-angle 0)
       (flag-offset-x 0)
       (flag-vx 0)
       (t 0))
  (entity/sprite! pole \"circle\" 8 \"gray\")
  (entity/sprite! flag \"circle\" 12 \"crimson\")
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (set! t (+ t 0.08))
      
      ;; pole sways left and right
      (set! pole-angle (* 0.3 (dsin t)))
      
      ;; flag tries to align with pole, but lags
      (let* ((target-offset (* 30 (dsin pole-angle)))
             (dx (- target-offset flag-offset-x))
             (accel (* dx 0.15)))
        (set! flag-vx (+ flag-vx accel))
        (set! flag-vx (* flag-vx 0.85))  ;; drag
        (set! flag-offset-x (+ flag-offset-x flag-vx)))
      
      ;; position flag relative to pole
      (let* ((pole-x (entity/x pole))
             (pole-y (entity/y pole))
             (flag-x (+ pole-x flag-offset-x))
             (flag-y (- pole-y 40)))
        (entity/set-pos! flag flag-x flag-y))
      
      (when (<= (world/frame) 300)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Gray circle sways gently left and right. Crimson circle above it lags behind the sway, whipping to the left as the pole tilts right, then swinging back, creating a fluttering, trailing motion.]

The flag's position is driven by the pole's angle, but with lag and damping—it's always playing catch-up, creating the whipping flutter.

---

## A spring-mounted antenna

A vehicle accelerates and brakes. An antenna mounted on top bends forward during acceleration, backward during braking, then settles upright.

```scheme
(let* ((vehicle (world/spawn 100 180))
       (antenna-base (world/spawn 100 160))
       (antenna-tip (world/spawn 100 140))
       (vx 0)
       (ax 0)
       (tip-offset-x 0)
       (tip-vx 0)
       (t 0))
  (entity/sprite! vehicle \"circle\" 20 \"navy\")
  (entity/sprite! antenna-base \"circle\" 5 \"silver\")
  (entity/sprite! antenna-tip \"circle\" 6 \"gold\")
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (set! t (+ t 1))
      
      ;; vehicle accelerates, then brakes
      (cond
        ((<= t 40)
         (set! ax 0.15))
        ((<= t 70)
         (set! ax -0.2))
        (else
         (set! ax 0)))
      
      (set! vx (+ vx ax))
      (set! vx (* vx 0.98))  ;; air resistance
      (entity/move! vehicle vx 0)
      
      ;; antenna base follows vehicle
      (entity/set-pos! antenna-base (entity/x vehicle) 160)
      
      ;; antenna tip reacts to acceleration (opposite direction)
      (let* ((force (* ax -8))  ;; inertia opposes acceleration
             (spring-force (* tip-offset-x -0.1))  ;; spring pulls back to center
             (total-force (+ force spring-force)))
        (set! tip-vx (+ tip-vx total-force))
        (set! tip-vx (* tip-vx 0.9))  ;; damping
        (set! tip-offset-x (+ tip-offset-x tip-vx)))
      
      (let ((base-x (entity/x antenna-base)))
        (entity/set-pos! antenna-tip (+ base-x tip-offset-x) 140))
      
      (when (<= t 200)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Navy circle accelerates to the right—gold circle above it bends backward (left). Navy circle brakes—gold circle whips forward (right), then oscillates back and forth, settling upright.]

The antenna's tip responds to the vehicle's acceleration with inertia—it bends opposite the acceleration, then springs back. This is secondary motion driven by force.

---

## A chain swinging from a moving hook

A hook moves in a circular path. A chain of segments hangs from it, each segment pulling on the next. The chain lags and swings.

```scheme
(let* ((hook (world/spawn 200 100))
       (seg-1 (world/spawn 200 120))
       (seg-2 (world/spawn 200 140))
       (seg-3 (world/spawn 200 160))
       (t 0))
  (entity/sprite! hook \"circle\" 8 \"darkgray\")
  (entity/sprite! seg-1 \"circle\" 7 \"gray\")
  (entity/sprite! seg-2 \"circle\" 7 \"lightgray\")
  (entity/sprite! seg-3 \"circle\" 7 \"gainsboro\")
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (set! t (+ t 0.06))
      
      ;; hook moves in a circle
      (let ((x (+ 200 (* 60 (dcos t))))
            (y (+ 100 (* 40 (dsin t)))))
        (entity/set-pos! hook x y))
      
      ;; each segment chases the one above with spring physics
      (let ((pull (lambda (follower leader rate)
                    (let* ((lx (entity/x leader))
                           (ly (entity/y leader))
                           (fx (entity/x follower))
                           (fy (entity/y follower))
                           (dx (- lx fx))
                           (dy (- ly fy)))
                      ;; pull toward leader, but also apply gravity
                      (entity/move! follower (* dx rate) (+ (* dy rate) 0.5))))))
        (pull seg-1 hook 0.18)
        (pull seg-2 seg-1 0.18)
        (pull seg-3 seg-2 0.18))
      
      (when (<= (world/frame) 400)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Dark gray circle orbits in a wide circle. Three lighter gray circles hang below it in a chain, swinging and lagging behind the hook's motion, trailing outward on the curves.]

Each segment is pulled toward the one above, but gravity also acts on it. The chain lags behind the hook and swings outward on the curves—secondary motion emerges from the interplay of forces.

