## Overlapping settle: a stack of blocks

A tower of blocks is nudged. The bottom block moves first, then the next, then the next. Each settles on its own schedule.

```scheme
(let* ((base (world/spawn 200 220))
       (block-1 (world/spawn 200 200))
       (block-2 (world/spawn 200 180))
       (block-3 (world/spawn 200 160))
       (base-vx 0)
       (v1x 0)
       (v2x 0)
       (v3x 0)
       (t 0))
  (entity/sprite! base \"circle\" 16 \"saddlebrown\")
  (entity/sprite! block-1 \"circle\" 14 \"peru\")
  (entity/sprite! block-2 \"circle\" 12 \"burlywood\")
  (entity/sprite! block-3 \"circle\" 10 \"wheat\")
  
  ;; nudge base at t=20
  (world/after 20
    (lambda ()
      (set! base-vx 3)))
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (set! t (+ t 1))
      
      ;; base drifts and settles
      (set! base-vx (* base-vx 0.92))
      (entity/move! base base-vx 0)
      
      ;; each block above tries to follow the one below with lag
      (let ((pull (lambda (v target-x)
                    (let* ((dx (- target-x (entity/x (lambda () 0))))  ;; placeholder
                           (accel (* dx 0.05)))
                      (+ v accel)))))
        
        ;; block-1 chases base
        (let ((dx (- (entity/x base) (entity/x block-1))))
          (set! v1x (+ v1x (* dx 0.08)))
          (set! v1x (* v1x 0.90)))
        (entity/move! block-1 v1x 0)
        
        ;; block-2 chases block-1
        (let ((dx (- (entity/x block-1) (entity/x block-2))))
          (set! v2x (+ v2x (* dx 0.08)))
          (set! v2x (* v2x 0.90)))
        (entity/move! block-2 v2x 0)
        
        ;; block-3 chases block-2
        (let ((dx (- (entity/x block-2) (entity/x block-3))))
          (set! v3x (+ v3x (* dx 0.08)))
          (set! v3x (* v3x 0.90)))
        (entity/move! block-3 v3x 0))
      
      (when (<= t 180)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Brown block at the bottom nudges right and settles. Three lighter blocks above it each follow with increasing lag—second block, then third, then top. Each settles on its own timing, creating a cascading wave of motion up the tower.]

The blocks settle in sequence. The base moves first, then each block above follows with delay. The top block is the last to settle—overlapping action rising through the stack.

