## A pendulum clock with three hands

A clock pendulum swings. The second hand ticks forward. The minute and hour hands lag behind, each moving on a slower schedule.

```scheme
(let* ((pendulum (world/spawn 200 180))
       (second-hand (world/spawn 200 100))
       (minute-hand (world/spawn 200 100))
       (hour-hand (world/spawn 200 100))
       (pendulum-angle 0.5)
       (pendulum-vel 0)
       (second-angle 0)
       (minute-angle 0)
       (hour-angle 0)
       (tick 0))
  (entity/sprite! pendulum \"circle\" 10 \"saddlebrown\")
  (entity/sprite! second-hand \"circle\" 8 \"red\")
  (entity/sprite! minute-hand \"circle\" 10 \"blue\")
  (entity/sprite! hour-hand \"circle\" 12 \"black\")
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      ;; pendulum swings
      (let ((accel (* (dsin pendulum-angle) -0.015)))
        (set! pendulum-vel (+ pendulum-vel accel))
        (set! pendulum-vel (* pendulum-vel 0.998))
        (set! pendulum-angle (+ pendulum-angle pendulum-vel)))
      (let ((x (+ 200 (* 50 (dsin pendulum-angle))))
            (y (+ 120 (* 50 (dcos pendulum-angle)))))
        (entity/set-pos! pendulum x y))
      
      ;; second hand ticks every 10 frames
      (set! tick (+ tick 1))
      (when (= (modulo tick 10) 0)
        (set! second-angle (+ second-angle (/ TAU 60))))
      
      ;; minute and hour hands lag behind
      (let ((minute-target (/ second-angle 60))
            (hour-target (/ second-angle 720)))
        (set! minute-angle (+ minute-angle (* (- minute-target minute-angle) 0.05)))
        (set! hour-angle (+ hour-angle (* (- hour-target hour-angle) 0.02))))
      
      ;; position hands
      (let ((sx (+ 200 (* 40 (dsin second-angle))))
            (sy (- 100 (* 40 (dcos second-angle))))
            (mx (+ 200 (* 30 (dsin minute-angle))))
            (my (- 100 (* 30 (dcos minute-angle))))
            (hx (+ 200 (* 20 (dsin hour-angle))))
            (hy (- 100 (* 20 (dcos hour-angle)))))
        (entity/set-pos! second-hand sx sy)
        (entity/set-pos! minute-hand mx my)
        (entity/set-pos! hour-hand hx hy))
      
      (when (<= (world/frame) 300)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Brown circle swings back and forth at the bottom. Three circles at the top rotate at different speeds—red ticks forward in discrete steps, blue lags behind with smooth motion, black lags furthest with the slowest drift.]

The pendulum is primary motion. The clock hands are secondary—each moves on its own schedule, lagging the layer above it.

---

## A banner that unfurls

A banner is rolled up at the top. It unfurls downward in a wave, each horizontal strip lagging behind the one above.

```scheme
(let* ((strips (map (lambda (i)
                      (let ((s (world/spawn 200 (+ 80 (* i 12)))))
                        (entity/sprite! s \"circle\" 10 \"crimson\")
                        (list s 0 0)))  ;; (entity y-offset velocity)
                    (list 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7)))
       (unfurl-start 20))
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (let ((frame (world/frame)))
        ;; each strip starts unfurling after the previous one
        (set! strips
          (map (lambda (strip-data i)
                 (let* ((strip (car strip-data))
                        (y-offset (cadr strip-data))
                        (vy (caddr strip-data))
                        (start-frame (+ unfurl-start (* i 5)))
                        (target-y 0))
                   (if (>= frame start-frame)
                       (let* ((dy (- target-y y-offset))
                              (accel (* dy 0.12)))
                         (set! vy (+ vy accel))
                         (set! vy (* vy 0.88))
                         (set! y-offset (+ y-offset vy)))
                       (set! y-offset -50))  ;; rolled up
                   (entity/set-pos! strip 200 (+ 80 (* i 12) y-offset))
                   (list strip y-offset vy)))
               strips
               (list 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7))))
      
      (when (<= (world/frame) 200)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Eight red circles arranged vertically. Starting from the top, each one drops downward in sequence with a slight delay, then bounces and settles into place, creating a cascading unfurl down the banner.]

Each strip starts its drop 5 frames after the previous one. The unfurl is overlapping action—the same motion (drop and settle), but staggered in time.

---

## A ragdoll that collapses

A standing figure collapses. The head falls first, then the torso, then the limbs, each part settling at its own rate.

```scheme
(let* ((head (world/spawn 200 120))
       (torso (world/spawn 200 145))
       (arm-l (world/spawn 185 150))
       (arm-r (world/spawn 215 150))
       (leg-l (world/spawn 195 170))
       (leg-r (world/spawn 205 170))
       (head-vy 0)
       (torso-vy 0)
       (arm-l-vy 0)
       (arm-r-vy 0)
       (leg-l-vy 0)
       (leg-r-vy 0)
       (collapsed #f))
  (entity/sprite! head \"circle\" 12 \"peachpuff\")
  (entity/sprite! torso \"circle\" 16 \"tan\")
  (entity/sprite! arm-l \"circle\" 8 \"sandybrown\")
  (entity/sprite! arm-r \"circle\" 8 \"sandybrown\")
  (entity/sprite! leg-l \"circle\" 10 \"peru\")
  (entity/sprite! leg-r \"circle\" 10 \"peru\")
  
  ;; collapse at frame 30
  (world/after 30
    (lambda ()
      (set! collapsed #t)))
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (when collapsed
        (let ((gravity 0.25)
              (ground 200)
              (damping 0.6))
          ;; head falls
          (set! head-vy (+ head-vy gravity))
          (entity/move! head 0 head-vy)
          (when (>= (entity/y head) (- ground 30))
            (entity/set-pos! head (entity/x head) (- ground 30))
            (set! head-vy (* head-vy (- damping))))
          
          ;; torso falls with delay
          (when (>= (world/frame) 35)
            (set! torso-vy (+ torso-vy gravity))
            (entity/move! torso 0 torso-vy)
            (when (>= (entity/y torso) (- ground 15))
              (entity/set-pos! torso (entity/x torso) (- ground 15))
              (set! torso-vy (* torso-vy (- damping)))))
          
          ;; arms fall with more delay
          (when (>= (world/frame) 42)
            (set! arm-l-vy (+ arm-l-vy gravity))
            (set! arm-r-vy (+ arm-r-vy gravity))
            (entity/move! arm-l 0 arm-l-vy)
            (entity/move! arm-r 0 arm-r-vy)
            (when (>= (entity/y arm-l) (- ground 10))
              (entity/set-pos! arm-l (entity/x arm-l) (- ground 10))
              (set! arm-l-vy (* arm-l-vy (- damping))))
            (when (>= (entity/y arm-r) (- ground 10))
              (entity/set-pos! arm-r (entity/x arm-r) (- ground 10))
              (set! arm-r-vy (* arm-r-vy (- damping)))))
          
          ;; legs fall last
          (when (>= (world/frame) 50)
            (set! leg-l-vy (+ leg-l-vy gravity))
            (set! leg-r-vy (+ leg-r-vy gravity))
            (entity/move! leg-l 0 leg-l-vy)
            (entity/move! leg-r 0 leg-r-vy)
            (when (>= (entity/y leg-l) ground)
              (entity/set-pos! leg-l (entity/x leg-l) ground)
              (set! leg-l-vy (* leg-l-vy (- damping))))
            (when (>= (entity/y leg-r) ground)
              (entity/set-pos! leg-r (entity/x leg-r) ground)
              (set! leg-r-vy (* leg-r-vy (- damping)))))))
      
      (when (<= (world/frame) 200)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Six circles arranged in a standing figure. At frame 30, the head (top) falls first and bounces. The torso follows, then the arms, then the legs—each part falling, bouncing, and settling in sequence, creating a cascading collapse.]

The collapse is pure overlapping action. Each body part falls on its own schedule, each bounces and settles independently. The result reads as a ragdoll, not a rigid statue.

---

## A whip that cracks

A handle moves forward sharply, then stops. A chain of segments trails behind, each lagging more. The tip moves fastest and cracks like a whip.

```scheme
(let* ((handle (world/spawn 100 150))
       (segments (map (lambda (i)
                        (let ((s (world/spawn (- 100 (* i 8)) 150)))
                          (entity/sprite! s \"circle\" (- 10 i) \"sienna\")
                          (list s 0 0)))  ;; (entity vx vy)
                      (list 0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7)))
       (handle-vx 0)
       (t 0))
  (entity/sprite! handle \"circle\" 12 \"saddlebrown\")
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (set! t (+ t 1))
      
      ;; handle accelerates forward, then stops
      (cond
        ((<= t 15)
         (set! handle-vx 8))
        ((<= t 18)
         (set! handle-vx (* handle-vx 0.3)))
        (else
         (set! handle-vx 0)))
      
      (entity/move! handle handle-vx 0)
      
      ;; each segment chases the one in front with increasing lag
      (set! segments
        (let loop ((segs segments)
                   (leader handle)
                   (i 0))
          (if (null? segs)
              '()
              (let* ((seg-data (car segs))
                     (seg (car seg-data))
                     (vx (cadr seg-data))
                     (vy (caddr seg-data))
                     (lx (entity/x leader))
                     (ly (entity/y leader))
                     (sx (entity/x seg))
                     (sy (entity/y seg))
                     (dx (- lx sx))
                     (dy (- ly sy))
                     (rate (- 0.4 (* i 0.04)))  ;; decreasing chase rate = more lag
                     (accel-x (* dx rate))
                     (accel-y (* dy rate)))
                (set! vx (+ vx accel-x))
                (set! vy (+ vy accel-y))
                (set! vx (* vx 0.88))
                (set! vy (* vy 0.88))
                (entity/move! seg vx vy)
                (cons (list seg vx vy)
                      (loop (cdr segs) seg (+ i 1)))))))
      
      (when (<= t 120)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Brown circle accelerates sharply to the right, then stops. Eight progressively smaller tan circles trail behind. As the handle stops, the segments whip forward in a wave, the tip moving fastest and cracking past the handle before settling back.]

The decreasing chase rate means segments further from the handle lag more. When the handle stops, the accumulated lag releases in a wave—the whip cracks.

---

## A tree branch bending under snow weight

Snow accumulates on a branch. The branch bends downward gradually. When the snow falls off, the branch springs back and oscillates.

```scheme
(let* ((base (world/spawn 150 120))
       (branch (world/spawn 220 140))
       (snow (world/spawn 220 130))
       (snow-mass 0)
       (branch-y 140)
       (branch-vy 0)
       (t 0))
  (entity/sprite! base \"circle\" 12 \"saddlebrown\")
  (entity/sprite! branch \"circle\" 10 \"sienna\")
  (entity/sprite! snow \"circle\" 8 \"white\")
  
  (world/after 1
    (lambda ()
      (set! t (+ t 1))
      
      ;; snow accumulates for 80 frames
      (when (<= t 80)
        (set! snow-mass (+ snow-mass 0.5)))
      
      ;; snow falls off at t=100
      (when (= t 100)
        (set! snow-mass 0))
      
      ;; branch bends under snow weight, springs back when relieved
      (let* ((weight-force (* snow-mass 0.3))
             (spring-force (* (- 140 branch-y) 0.08))
             (total-force (+ spring-force (- weight-force))))
        (set! branch-vy (+ branch-vy total-force))
        (set! branch-vy (* branch-vy 0.92))
        (set! branch-y (+ branch-y branch-vy)))
      
      (entity/set-pos! branch 220 branch-y)
      (if (> snow-mass 0)
          (entity/set-pos! snow 220 (- branch-y 10))
          (entity/set-pos! snow 220 (+ branch-y 50)))  ;; snow on ground
      
      (when (<= t 180)
        (world/after 1 (world/current-callback))))))
```

[VISUAL: Brown circle at left (tree trunk). Tan circle bends gradually downward as white circle grows. At frame 100, white circle falls, and tan circle springs back upward, oscillating and settling back to its original height.]

The branch's bend is the primary motion (driven by snow weight). The spring-back and oscillation is follow-through—the motion continues past the relief point, then settles.

