## Notes and Additional Considerations from r1 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r1 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### A Single Trailing Element

The simplest secondary motion: one object follows another, always a fixed distance behind in *time*, not space.

```scheme
(let ((leader-x 100)
      (follower-x 100)
      (target-x 400)
      (lag 0.08))
  (motion/loop 180
    (lambda (frame)
      (set! leader-x (+ leader-x (* (- target-x leader-x) 0.1)))
      (set! follower-x (+ follower-x (* (- leader-x follower-x) lag)))
      (world/clear)
      (entity/circle leader-x 200 12 \"coral\")
      (entity/circle follower-x 200 8 \"skyblue\")
      (world/paint))))
```

[VISUAL: Two circles travel right; the blue one lags smoothly behind the coral leader, maintaining separation even as both slow toward the target.]

The follower eases toward *where the leader is now*, not where it was. The smaller the lag constant, the tighter the follow.

---


### Lag on a Vertical Drop

A weight on a string: the hand drops, the weight follows a beat later.

```scheme
(let ((hand-y 100)
      (weight-y 100)
      (time 0))
  (motion/loop 120
    (lambda (frame)
      (set! time (+ time 1))
      (set! hand-y (if (< time 30) 100 300))
      (set! weight-y (+ weight-y (* (- hand-y weight-y) 0.12)))
      (world/clear)
      (entity/line 250 hand-y 250 weight-y \"gray\")
      (entity/circle 250 hand-y 6 \"pink\")
